This is encouraging. I think Novelty Searching will be the next thing I wil=
l implement in RubyNEAT.
On Friday, April 25, 2014 1:22 PM, "jclune@gmail.c=
om" <jclune@...> wrote:
 
=C2=A0 
Hello all,

Many people are skeptic=
al of Novelty Search, believing it to be a random search. Ken and Joel have=
 responded that NS is interesting in part because across generations it acc=
umulates information about how to explore the environment.=C2=A0

Along wit=
h my Ph.D. student Roby Velez, I=E2=80=99m pleased to announce a new paper =
that investigates exactly that question. Before you read what we found, wha=
t do you predict would happen?
	* Will Novelty Search learn more explorator=
y skills than random search?
	* More than a traditional, objective-driven E=
A?=C2=A0

We=E2=80=99d love to hear if your predictions were right and if y=
ou=E2=80=99re surprised by the answers. We were!

Video summary of the pape=
r:=C2=A0http://youtu.be/P-EqOBqjTyU

Cite: Velez R, Clune J (2014) Novelty =
Search Creates Robots with General Skills for Exploration. Proceedings of t=
he Genetic=C2=A0and Evolutionary Computation Conference.

PDF:=C2=A0http://=
jeffclune.com/publications/2014-Velez-Clune-NS-Learns-Skills-GECCO.pdf

Abs=
tract: Novelty Search, a new type of Evolutionary Algorithm, has shown much=
 promise in the last few years. Instead of selecting for phenotypes that=C2=
=A0are closer to an objective, Novelty Search assigns rewards based on how =
different the phenotypes are from those already generated. A common=C2=A0cr=
iticism of Novelty Search is that it is effectively random or exhaustive se=
arch because it tries solutions in an unordered manner until a=C2=A0correct=
 one is found. Its creators respond that over time Novelty Search accumulat=
es information about the environment in the form of skills=C2=A0relevant to=
 reaching uncharted territory, but to date no evidence for that hypothesis =
has been presented. In this paper we test that hypothesis by=C2=A0transferr=
ing robots evolved under Novelty Search to new environments (here, mazes) t=
o see if the skills they=E2=80=99ve acquired generalize. Three=C2=A0lines o=
f evidence support the claim that Novelty Search agents do indeed learn gen=
eral exploration
 skills. First, robot controllers evolved via=C2=A0Novelty=
 Search in one maze and then transferred to a new maze explore significantl=
y more of the new environment than non-evolved=C2=A0(randomly generated) ag=
ents. Second, a Novelty Search process to solve the new mazes works signifi=
cantly faster when seeded with the=C2=A0transferred controllers versus rand=
omly-generated ones. Third, no significant difference exists when comparing=
 two types of transferred=C2=A0agents: those evolved in the original maze u=
nder (1) Novelty Search vs. (2) a traditional, objective-based fitness func=
tion. The evidence=C2=A0gathered suggests that, like traditional Evolutiona=
ry Algorithms with objective-based fitness functions, Novelty Search is not=
 a random or=C2=A0exhaustive search process, but instead is accumulating in=
formation about the environment, resulting in phenotypes possessing skills =
needed to=C2=A0explore their world.





Best regards,
Jeff Clune
